                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      TCIL to exit Bharti Hexacom
                            
	New Delhi, March 3 (Agencies): State-run Telecommunications Consultants India Ltd (TCIL) today said it would exit its joint venture with the Bharti group  Bharti Hexacom  by selling its 30 per cent stake in the company.        
	TCIL has appointed Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu India as the financial adviser for the divestment.         
	TCIL intends to divest its equity represented by 7.50 crore equity shares of nominal value of Rs 10 each, aggregating to 30 per cent of the total paid-up equity share capital, in Bharti Hexacom to an investor, TCIL said.        
	At present, Bharti holds 70 per cent and TCIL holds the remaining 30 per cent in Bharti Hexacom.        
	Meanwhile, Bharti Airtel has elevated Sanjay Kapoor as its chief executive for India and South Asia from March 1, a month earlier than previously announced. Kapoor will take over from Manoj Kohli, who will now head Bhartis international business unit.                                                                                                                                       
